caption: The crab egg Benedict is AMAZING! 3 stars for that alone! Ube pancake isn’t what I thought it would be. I love all things Ube and thought I’d be obsessed but the butter is so heavy and really all you can taste. My husband liked it so giving another star for that. I also didn’t like that they give you plastic utensils (wasteful and flimsy). The food also took really long which shouldn’t really be the case for breakfast

The wait was about an hour for two people, but they allow you to come back if you stay close to the restaurant. The choco waffles were phenomenal- the best waffles I’ve ever had. Without syrup even! The pork belly Benedict, tator tots, and the iced coffee were good too!
Great food awesome atmosphere the plates are peices of art

Great pancakes! Good variety of breakfast foods. The interior has a pretty unique look with the lights and railings. Tends to be very busy during lunch due to limited seating. Great overall though.

I’ve visited Oahu a few times now but this was my first time trying YogurStory. What drew me here were their ube pancakes. These pancakes are divine... like amazing to not only look at but also to bite into. Subtly sweet, smooth, and scrumptious ube goodness on top some of the best pancakes ever. The pancake stack by themselves are the perfect texture and bite. I would totally recommend Yorgurstory to anyone looking for great ube pancakes

Food was great, but service was horrible. They took my order,  brought my food, never came back to check on me. I had to get up, walk across the restaurant and tell the staff I needed some drinks. I should never have to get up for just some thing to drink...
Great food and service.
SO much food!

Tasty sweet, savory and sandwich options, lots of variety to choose from. Adult beverages don't appear on the menu but are available upon request. Attentive staff and quick service. I would definitely go back to try more of the menu.

Yogur story serves up the most amazing ube pancakes. These pancakes by themselves are incredible. I’ve had these twice within this past week because they are really that good. It’s funny, in case you were wondering like I did, I asked the waiter what “Yogur” means, and the worker told me that even they don’t really know. The original owner may have accidentally left out the “T” in yogurt or tried to create a new word. Whatever the case, even the workers don’t know what Yogur means.

Our go-to breakfasts spot. Lots of parking and really nice atmosphere. Get there early before 8:30 if you don’t want to wait to be seated or you can reserve your spot in line through the Yelp app. It’s pretty pricey and some things are really not worth it, like basic waffle/ French toast/ pancakes. The breakfast dishes are delicious and well portioned, two could eat with one dish such as the eggs Benedict or skillet eggs. Must try place for locals and tourists alike!
Tasty breakfast & brunch place
Delicious food, friendly staff, and a cute place to eat! They were super busy but very accommodating and helped us out even though we were a little late to our reservation.
Usually it's pretty good here. But this time it was mediocre.
Did an spinach 🍄 swiss cheese 🧀 omelette with potato wedges. First rate👍. As was was my friend's classic Benedict. And as always the ☕ was great 🤗 and the refills came like clockwork.
We had the BAE Benedict, crab cake Benedict, and the Red Carpet Waffles. All delicious!

This is one of the best breakfast places I've been to!!! Waited about 10-15 minutes to get seated because it's jam-packed which is not bad. So if you're planning to come here, come early. You have to put in your name on their tablet and phone number to be on their waitlist. The place is nice and clean with cool pictures on the walls and lighting fixtures. It has a mezzanine and patio dining spaces. Both are nice, but I prefer the mezzanine because you get to see the whole restaurant. We ordered their three best sellers: crab benedict, prime rib loco moco and their most famous ube pancake. Boy oh boy, all were delicious!! The prime rib is cooked to perfection and the gravy complemented it very well. The crabcakes on the benedict are thick and so flavorful. And the ube pancakes are immaculate, so soft and the sauce made it so much better. I'd definitely be back!
Great food and service!!
The wait is long however you can sign up for the wait list using Yelp. The food was so with the wait though. The crab cakes were 90% crab 10% 100% amazing.
The food was underwhelming. I had very high expectations from the pics on yelp, but it was just average. Not bad, not exceptional. The ube pancakes were good.
Ube pancakes are a must
Great server.  Good food.   Reasonably priced.
First time here and will definitely be going back. Fast service, professional staff and yummy food.

So. Good. SO. GOOD. This place was amazing! I ordered the crab cake eggs Benedict and it was to die for! I got mine with 2 hash browns (patties) and asparagus. The eggs were perfectly poached, the crab cakes were a thick, generous size, with lots of crab (sometimes the veggies can overpower the crab, but these cakes were dominantly crab!), and they were on a purple ube piece of bread (English muffin consistency). So good, will 100% order again. My husband got a simple meal, the big breakfast combo with over easy eggs, and he was raving about how perfect his meal was as well. We got ube pancakes to share, and s’mores waffles for the kids. The ube pancakes were amazing, I love the thick ube sauce ontop, just REALLY really good. Perfectly cooked. Highly recommend. For some reason we didn’t like the s’mores waffles. I’m a huge s’mores fan so I was sorely disappointed. They had marshmallow and chocolate and graham crumbles, it looked amazing, but man it tasted really weird. Nobody ate it. But that doesn’t take away from our 5 star experience because the rest of the food was SO beyond delicious.  I do wish there were kids options. It’s quite expensive to buy a whole big adult meal for picky kids that don’t eat much. Felt like a waste of money for them.

I think in the beginning this restaurant was great. Now the quality has gone down. Had pork belly with fried rice.  The pork belly was tough and dry. If anything, they should shrink the menu. Take the things they are known for and elevate them. Focus on quality over quantity!

I got the Prime rib skillet. The tender chunks of prime rib with bell peppers and crispy tater tots topped with an egg is the perfect combination of textures and flavors. Highly recommend and it won't break the bank.

We always enjoy the food here. My go-to fav is the Prime Rib Loco Moco, second is the Eggs Benedict. A few other notable items: Ube Pancakes and Red Velvet Waffles. My SO recommended we brunch at Yogur Story based solely on the ube pancakes, and I am thrilled that she made the recommendation! This was hands down one of the best meals I've had on Oahu.  First things first: you're going to wait, that's just the nature of the beast. or is it? (more on that in a bit) When we walked up, we saw that the seats under the outside canopy were all taken by other guests waiting to have their names called. I walked in, jotted down my name and party size, and was told it'd be about 40 mins (ended up being slightly shorter - yay). Once my name was called, we were directed upstairs - not lead - and took our seats. The hostess was kind enough to let us store our bags near her station, which was appreciated.  Now, about that wait: I don't understand the necessity of keeping people waiting outside in the sun. During the entire time we brunched, I never saw anyone aside from restaurant staff at the close of business occupying the tables at one whole side of the upstairs area. Even the larger general floor area where we were seated maintained at least three to four empty tables. While it's possible that such is their system to not overwhelm the kitchen, I nevertheless feel that people would rather be told that the kitchen is a bit backed up whilst sitting cool inside rather than out in the heat.  About those ube pancakes: they are delicious; however, they also can prove to be a bit much. I mean, they are literally just drenched in the ube sauce, so unless you're all in for the full experience, I'd recommend ordering something savory with which to cut their sweetness, or else splitting them with someone else. It's a lot to take on just yourself.  My SO and I chose to pair the ube pancakes with the K-Town chicken & waffle, which was yet another excellent choice on her part. The chicken turned out to be boneless strips rather than wings, which suited us both just fine. The few bites of waffle drenched in Korean barbecue sauce were delightful; however, my SO did note that they were too salty for her tastes.  Our server was attentive without being intrusive/disruptive, which is evidently a much harder skill to master than you might imagine.  Note that there is but a single unisex bathroom on the second floor, and by the time I got around to using it, there were drying napkins spread nearly all across the floor. While that will most likely not be the case for everyone, I found the lack of attentiveness to the bathroom to be notable.  Overall, Yogur Story is undoubtedly a great choice for brunch in Honolulu; so much so, that I'm even tempted to return for what I saw of their dinner menu.  Should any of you ever learn the history of why it is named as it is, please do share!
